A Republican strategy to hinder Obama’s re-election
The Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
The Brennan Center considers the latter a myth and states that electoral fraud is less common in the United States than the number of people who die from lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have found no more than 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will in part undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
And on that same line a majority of U.S. governments enacted, starting in 2009, new laws that hindered the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 election, which saw the increase of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
Consequently, in 2011, 180 bills were introduced that restricted the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
New electoral laws require voters to present an identity card with a photograph, in addition to a proof of American citizenship.
Moreover, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on the day of the vote and withdraw their right to vote from citizens with a criminal background.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present an identity card with photography.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
For this reason, the Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present an identity card with photography.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as the Social Security card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, that is, 21 million people of voting age, do not have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity card with these characteristics.
But often obtaining the required identity card costs more than a hundred dollars.
As a result, the new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people who earn less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states, students, voters who vote most for Democratic candidates, cannot use the photo-issued ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states authorize members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for Republican parties to use documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004 no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to make such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have adopted laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
These measures clearly seek to limit Hispanic vote.
It seems that two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers supported certain laws in 2011 that abolished voter registration on the same day of polls in eight states.
In addition, they limited the right of individuals and groups to create an aid service for voters who wished to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general elections, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
Measures taken since 2009 have resulted in a decrease in the registration rate for new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers adopted laws in five other states that favored reducing the pre-voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida election, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state’s voters.
In the case of Hispanic people, the same thing happened.
These represent only 11% of the voters, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, which make up 76% of the electorate, make up no more than 46% of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have fervently opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney’s Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
It was possible, in part, to limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted the law requiring the presentation of an identity card with photography.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted, as it is clear that they aim to influence the results of 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required in the electoral college to achieve the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these legislative changes at the scale of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will in part undermine the American democratic system.
