The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated a huge shock last summer, and rightly.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of all that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And moreover, it is the particle whose existence the standard model predicted: our best or "less bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been observed empirically.
But to the physicists it is not entirely clear that this is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it resembles a lot the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
Furthermore, new data revealed this week at a major physics conference held in Kyoto seems to confirm that it is, although more data still lacking to be completely secure.
Anyway, we assume that this is Higgs, because the chances of mistaking seem little. We will see what it is about.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to violate that rule and do not try too much, because it will end up hurting itself.
Although the physics of particles is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, roughly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we encounter the good citizens called Fermiones, who wisely obey Pauli’s beginning.
And on the other hand there are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, of which we will not talk here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, I should emphasize here, are not the exotic beasts we could believe.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or "light particle" that acts as the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" is born an electromagnetic wave (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "force carrier" bosons.
More stable field
The same happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it, it requires extremely high energies, a bit as if it were an ice pond in which only a thick rock could slide through the surface.
Therefore, it takes an immense particle accelerator such as that of CERN (the great hadron collider is a 27-km-circumference ring!) to reach such energy levels.
Analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stand by itself glued to the door of a fridge.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not have it.
Now, what can all these investigations “contribute?” asks Ms. Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (MS), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and MS predictions.
Many, for their part, fervently wish that they meet, as the smallest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that covers certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (other ups!).
But we have not found such differences at CERN so far.
Impacts
The repercussions of such investigations in our day-to-day lives are difficult to predict, but we don’t think we’re mistaken in saying it won’t have any.
In the early 1960s, laser pioneers in laboratories did not suspect at all the revolution that their work would bring about.
They encountered scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, initially the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Imagine...
And in addition, the applications can also proceed from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light collector in 1969 in the course of his optical research.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this pick-up now serves as an "eye" for all digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
