How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two electronic addresses in the form of email.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed via a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are contained in the public book of accounts, which is spread throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction into that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file cutting, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "crossing" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zero at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, in order to commit a fraud, a user would like to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions as valid; the other would remain orphaned, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is divided into two regularly, likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to one hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in calculation power.
The life of the network has its ups and downs.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been attacked and stolen bitcoins in deposit.
“The fault used does not affect the same protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money loss thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Weight actors like Wikipedia reject such payments.
Others, such as the WordPress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Insitit in Israel, analyzed the book and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins don’t circulate.
In November, the “giant sales” were launched.
"There were $30,000 exchanged," rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on this currency, believes quite a lot in the potential of this technology as well as in the transaction network.
Their system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are cheaper.
The carrier also manages its identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to run in shops, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
It is enough for them to provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
“It will take a while for Bitcoin to impose itself, but in 2013 there could be a change,” he predicts.
Furthermore, in its report, the ECB plans to re-evaluate the various risks, today considered high, in the event that this currency succeeds.
