Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system,” explains Alexis Blouet, who prepares a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around article 220, as the terms used imitate religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question that could arise in the future would be to what extent the civilian judges are competent to rule above all this.”
Beyond its religious nature, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms concerning the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few in comparison to those they were during the previous regime.
Another conflicting point: the powers conferred on the army.
According to the military’s desire, the revision of the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Nor will prosecution of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as requested by human rights associations.
They also showed their concerns regarding the text, which they consider liberticide.
The crime of blasphemy continues and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no article emphasizes the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
