If it weren't, they wouldn't have any benefit to collaborate with our office, don't you think?
As for our country's legislation, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean for your Office?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control actions.
Since we carry out ex post checks, a certain delay is needed.
For now, we see in the process of preparing future controls: we have launched a new "non-economic risk detection" tool, through which we have passed nearly 14,000 public tenders, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are corrected and the like.
Do you consider the adoption of this law to be beneficial or rather a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope it is.
The problem that can arise is that the regulation "shall be hardened" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already under the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (e.g. in the case of regional regional council operational programmes), and every non-compliance with laws on public awards meant a breach of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to harden the law in this way?
I don't think it's this way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal decision, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only be able to create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this started path leads us.
The Prime Minister recently declared that the SDG would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the "švarc" system forbidden or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way, and if it prohibits anything, then even the Prime Minister of the government cannot prevent the action of the Office which is obliged to carry out such checks and impose obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and we allow it," but you can't say that we're going to pretend nothing.
In the law on public procurement, the regulations are quite strict as to how it should be acted formally, and that is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for failing to meet formal demands.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. That is, in my opinion, what we lack.
