Poland and the cosmos.
At the meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency countries held last week, Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second ESA member country of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began an intense collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in the agency’s project commission.
However, Poland’s path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the conference by A. Šternfeld at the astronomical observatory in Warsaw in which, on 6 December 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the assistants indifferent, and years later Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won in France the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Award for their "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a major driver of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, he was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he put his name on one of the craters of the hidden face of the moon.
Already in 1925 a drain was built in Poland that was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is unknown who was the author of the proposal and the details of the project are not known either.
It is unclear whether the rocket was to be used for starting the dresin or for its braking.
Information about this dresine is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
In 1933 the Polish artillery began to devote itself to missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustavem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the investigation has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the specialized press appeared the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by engineer Rohoziński and the following year was published the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was responsible for all projects of missile techniques for military use and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, society is first referenced with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronomy.
In one of them, by Professor M. Subotowicze, it was proposed to create a society that would devote itself to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Astronautic Society (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Astronautic Federation (founded in 1951) and in the autumn of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice president of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He served in this position until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) probe rocket, which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had a peak of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg of weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 aerial testing of the two-stage RM-2 rockets began in the Błędów desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of rocket in development was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the wind of height.
In 1962, however, work was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differentiated from each other by the space available for scientific apparatus.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for volume was 0.4 litres, in the Meteor-1B 0.34 litres and in the Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum peak in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first aerial testing began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
Subsequently the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined the research of cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remek.
The suspension of the social labour law is not the solution.
Last week the constitutional court suspended the law on social work.
The resolution sparked a heated discussion in society.
It will of course be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less regulatory.
Consequently, this means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, along with unrestrained financial speculation.
The effect of large differences in labour costs (of wages) produces economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the importation of cheap goods, attempts to shorten distances and to this end "provoks a decrease" of the price of the competitor with the aim of gaining most of the market and thus increasing its profit margin.
On a large scale, for most entrepreneurs, it means moving production abroad, buying cheaper there or disappearing, resulting in high unemployment in those countries where the price of labour is higher compared to other economies.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and therefore is not responsible for the unemployment generated by this phenomenon, the social expenditure of the state necessarily grows.
This whole situation encourages the total disinterest of entrepreneurs in paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damage they have caused in their desire to obtain profits.
The situation is so universally known that it is not necessary to present concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of those countries are forced to compete with the objective of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thus attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own population without taking into account the social decline.
This is evident in particular in the changes to existing laws.
The aim is to force the population to accept the dictatorship of private capital, especially with regard to wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other hand, through the restricted right of employees as regards labour rights.
The result is growing poverty along with increasing differences between poor and rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot keep up with their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of aid reaches a million.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, a rather frequent case occurs: employees with such a low wage that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
Such a scandal was made public related to the situation of the auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament.
Savings from virtually all southern EU states lead, without a doubt, to the same situation: people, pressured by a steep decline of their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the nineteenth century or to miserably live on the limits of society, hoping that one day they will arrive in the private investing capital country.
Is it necessary to wonder where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty moves from one country to another or never comes, since Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a small part of a European wage.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media affirm to the satiety that the state should not bring capital to the economy, that directing the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by interfering in control.
Then it is necessary to wonder whether private capital does not influence its egoism on the political march and, therefore, on the whole state.
In this case, the answer is clearly affirmative.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and ubiquitous, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the sphere of corruption, in mutual favors, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: State ministries, in the absence of financial means, commission the drafting of bills to private legal companies, which are often linked to industry.
This type of bill is later passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
Thus, all power emanates not from the people, as proclaimed in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation find themselves quickly in a situation such as Appiános describes in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the times of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state has long been disintegrating and the administrations have been occupied by force."
In exchange for bribes, favors obtained illegitimately and helps to finance stones or swords.
The bribery and corruption spread unimpededly and the people went to the polls with the vote paved in advance"... "there were no people with character that would aspire to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganisation, the state was eight months without consuls"... "He began to talk seriously that the only remedy for such a serious self-cratic situation was necessary."
The conclusion, as in ancient times, is that today’s society is based on disregarded preferences for individual benefit without taking into account common interests.
Private capital is not, in its essence, capable of understanding and claiming the benefits of the whole society.
The result is the same as that of then, an unprecedented decline of the elite, without an effort being made to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unrestrained liberalization of economic systems in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
With regard to the current situation, it is possible to consider the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of a liberal democracy, as a definite pause, awaiting the next coup.
The truly devastating fact is that today’s elite completely ignores the losses of hundreds of thousands of lives, social and humanitarian catastrophes that we have witnessed, as well as crimes against humanity, as we know them in ancient and recent history.
The suspension of the public procurement law is not the solution; at least not in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both internationally and within the EU, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue searching for other ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution is through concrete socio-political reforms, which reinforce both the participation of state capital and the influence of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
