In November 1979, a group of Islamist student demonstrators occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 graduates hostage.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned Shah Mohamed Réza Páhlevi, who after the revolution fled to the United States, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation offered no positive prospect: tossing the Shah on board could not afford it, since, if it did, it jeopardized the trust of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within its reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which subsequently intensified further with the failed attempt to free hostages by force.
The incarcerated diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government’s negotiating intervention.
In the US, his fate caused a wave of solidarity and animation against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck thematizes an episode of this story, which harvested a small hit for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated trip, they ended up at the residence of the Canadian embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helping a covert story to achieve an extravagant point: they came out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that examined the location in the country for the shoot of a science fiction superproduction.
Gender combination
The plan drawn by "exfiltration" expert Toni Mendez required the collaboration of Hollywood.
To make the lie seem true, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society even had a real office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a singular combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a deception (an example may be the Ocean's Eleven series).
The film combines moods. On the one hand we find well-documented sequences of Tehran. In the credit sequence are shown iconic photographs of the era of events, which were plasmated in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes somewhat lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And in addition, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: suited men analyzing the situation at the negotiating table, in the office halls, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been mocked, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Little Goodbye, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town: City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is the first Affleck film in which the action does not take place in the city of Boston, where he was raised.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed ancient film directors above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck demonstrates it in Argo, where Tehran is "wheeling" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place on the streets, in the reconstruction of true events. The introductory sequence of the embassy takeover is impressive for its synoptic ability which, at the same time, conveys the excitement of disconcert and lack of prediction that arises when, somewhere, the story takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect on fictional scenes (the impostor team at the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
Sometimes it adds something to the reality: here not everything comes out so elegantly (the scene in which the crisis at Tehran airport is stalking, the diversion of a call to America and the unbridled quest behind its track become madness).
The weakness of Argo is the uncontrol that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not, much less, the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck’s film loses a bit of dramatic trace, but it is a film that can be followed with a moderate interest, appreciate its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 1970s.
But if it collapses, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a real story and as a proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services may be, it is enough.
