The architectural studio MVRDV demonstrates that true adventures are not just in the head - in the example of the library of Spijkenisse and the newly finished "mountain of books"- 2 photos
“I think the building is funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there’s something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a passing by the street.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company near the library, says: “In addition, the building is beautiful.”
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have internet, tablets and e-books.
No one goes into those old-fashioned libraries for good, right?
Spijkenisse, a bedroom town located at the gates of Rotterdam that barely deserves a fleeting visit, boasts the dubious honour of having risen with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this embarrassing situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute somehow to the general culture and copy the seven fictional bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated armed concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that’s how policy makers decided that there was only one possibility to improve the statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architectural studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for fun buildings at the same time as cynical, took the theme with his usual serenity and attended the competition presentation in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile in his face.
And as the jury looked perplexed around him and shrugged on his shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here is my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg.”
Nine years later, the €30 million mountain rises in the intended place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of house and townhouse buildings.
In early November the mountain of books was awarded the second award "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
Thus, the small town without history, which to date had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white façade one would rather intuit a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression is that it is a book paradise under a cheeser.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountainous massif, but the real lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with their topography every step of their climbing to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to embrace with the view, the annealed brick floor and elegant headlamps unmistakably support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
As you lift your eyes, you can see the park benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Normally the book shelves are arranged along the façade and in the center a huge dark room is opened which is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to put up the classic spatial configuration and pull the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserves the black shelves that assume the functions of wall covering, parapet and railing at the same time.
The sight, touch and smell are strange.
Even the most current architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the city of Spijkenisse.
And that’s like a day, on a Friesian farm, we encounter the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in the greenhouses and fields of the Netherlands, a small-millimeter thick plastic fabric is used as a basis for holding the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine fabric lasts two seasons and is then discarded.
For the library, this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, until irons of four centimeters thick were obtained.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a blend of new car and sneaker.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but there you can also enjoy some tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining adequate atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"Although it is hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge crystal pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden fences located in the transverse direction of the glass facade serve to shade and absorb most of the rays of the sun.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is about automatic shutters.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical worker in the Information Technology sector, has already dared to put his foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has also been there.
Similarly, traditional Chinese medicine professor Cynthia Bogarde has visited the library. She qualifies the "Boekenberg" as the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
In this way, it is intended to fill, at the moment, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; currently it has 70,000 copies.
The concept has shut down deep.
The shelves are full.
“There is nothing worse than a half empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain bond with this building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of the library.
Even if he's just there to adorn.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved all a success in that queen discipline that in specialized slang is known as "creating an identity".
The city of Spijkenisse has written a piece of the history of literature.
Regardless of how young and uncultivated he may be.
Finally a starting point to shape your identity.
