"Brand Protection" in China: When Puma and Armani Suddenly Become Chinese Brands
Armani is a world-renowned brand and Polo Ralph Lauren as well.
What is Armani Polo?
Behind this name is a name officially registered in China but it has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the true eponymes do not file a lawsuit.
Even then it is unclear whether they will be given the right.
“Foreigners find it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China,” says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at the Taylor Wessing firm specializing in violations of protection rights in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters to register their brands.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada, Prada-Kny is registered.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as has happened to the sports goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens an archive in which it holds seats at the Beijing brand office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the Zegna DF Puma brand, an artificial name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities there are large warehouses of several plants dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, the cases of Pattloch are of another nature. On behalf of his customers, he struggles against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying brand.
The word originates from the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan".
It refers to women who have "fished" a rich man.
Chinese authorities do not feel guilty
“It’s harmful to the business, we have to fight it,” demands Pattloch.
“The mark makes water, the monopoly position disappears and the damage that the image suffers is enormous.”
The financial losses and process costs of the affected sectors are billionaire, especially in the case of luxury iconic products.
According to data from market analysis firm CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros a year, China is, in size, the third largest market for luxury goods and the largest growing market.
However, to achieve the cancellation of dubious legal entries in the trademark registration is complicated and also costs a lot of money.
The processes can be prolonged for up to nine years and the outcome is uncertain.
Pattloch talks about cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because it had passed so long that the name the lawsuit has already become a "market reality".
“If the plaintiff is bad luck, he may even have to pay the plagiarist money because the process has damaged the plagiarist’s trademark in China,” Pattloch said.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the most well-known cases have to do with graphical elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That’s why today the Chinese can still use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
The Volvo buyer, Geely, initially used a white and blue logo that largely reminded BMW; the case was addressed in court and Geely had to modify it.
The clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo depicted a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO brand office in Beijing acknowledges that in 2010 they encountered difficulties due to a shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, “the work emergency situation returned to normal.”
In this way, the number of unprocessed complaints has been reduced by 22%.
Almost 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 complaints remain unresolved.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As usual in China, the figures are surprising.
Last year, the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, nearly a third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means that China is leading the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive year, the brand office notes.
It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, which amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan would have been packed for rights.
In other words, this means that on average each entry costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting against this costs a lot of money, as shown by the case of the German family company Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese imitator.
While the Germans have succeeded in stopping the illegal manufacturing of imitation car parts,
the imitator has managed to secure Chinese rights on the Freudenberg brand.
“We have caused this situation ourselves because in Germany surnames are not protected,” says Hanno Wentzler, President and Chief Executive Officer of Freudenberg Chemical Specialties in Munich.
The CTMO brand office also rejected the Munich’s appeal.
In the next two instances Freudenberg was given the right, but the opposite side continues to fight today.
We have to be very careful
The case has now reached the doors of the Supreme Court of Justice, where it remains pending a resolution.
Wentzler is confident that he will be able to settle the issue favorably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that “the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time.”
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; the business archive has had to review files up to 100 years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposite side a "six-digit sum in euros" with the aim of reaching a friendly deal, but it was unsuccessful.
“This shows how much we care about,” Wentzler says.
The dangers in the Far East threaten even to affect Europe.
Specifically if the imitators are assured the rights to unprotected trademarks there.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The group has long been leaving this commercial area, but has managed to prevent registration.
“We have to be very careful,” Wentzler says.
Both he and attorney Pattloch recommend that German companies be extremely prudent in doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark law, but what has to be done is to “register everything that can be protected in China as well,” as Wentzler notes.
Otherwise, the subject may be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, if Freudenberg lost the last assault of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the contrary party license rights by his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or in the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
