Bradley Manning did not denounce ill-treatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors try to deal with Bradley Manning's abuse allegations during his stay in prison
Trial focuses on Manning's period at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case to be dismissed on the basis that Manning's imprisonment was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove Friday that Soldier Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. history, lost multiple opportunities to denounce the ill-treatment he now claims he suffered while in military detention.
During the prosecutor’s interrogation of Manning at a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney Commander Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits of unit officers Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaint about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which was carried out during a hearing conducted following the defence’s request that the case be dismissed since his imprisonment had been harsh and that this had already entailed sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning had testified that he had thought of committing suicide while he was detained.
The army’s intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on service in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers filled in after Manning's visits during his arrest at Quantico military prison, where he was imprisoned in maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officials would have asked Manning questions and noted his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had qualified the treatment given by the cellers as “excellent” and the treatment received at the facilities in general as “very professional.”
The forms show no report of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern on some issues and that the officers who visited him had spoken of those issues and had indicated to him that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record those issues in the record.
"They wrote 'without incidents' (after talking about the problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean that I wouldn't have mentioned any problems," Manning said.
Judge Denise Lind also asked Manning why she had not reported the treatment she received during the January 2011 meeting with a council in charge of examining suicide intentions she had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was.
The military said they had put him under that restrictive regime, which is a degree below that of possible suicide surveillance, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the chief executive to know that I was okay and (I wanted) to stop being under injury prevention... to be able to enjoy what, in my view, is a better quality of life,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison located at the Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness due to heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage,” Manning explained Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning claimed that, once moved to Quantico, he spent most of the days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, without company.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, some slippers, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he was trying to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light from the outside pointing to his eyes while he was asleep.
He said that if the cellers couldn’t see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
In January 2011, Manning’s attorney filed a formal complaint regarding the treatment he received.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in Thursday’s statement, according to which, after being forced one night to sleep naked in his Quantico cell, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of the jailers and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the counting.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced by the cellier's order that he should drop the blanket with which he could have been covered, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his slippers to injure himself but that he had not.
Manning testified that that night his underwear, slippers and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he had during his stay in prison and drastically reduce his sentence in case he was convicted in the war council, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it intends to make Manning guilty of minor crimes and defend other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has argued that Manning was detained in accordance with the rules of application to all detainees who are in maximum custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegally provoking the publication of information on the Internet, leakage of national defense information, and theft of property or public records.
If he is found guilty of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
