UNASUR Summit Ends Without Making Public Lima Declaration
The 6th Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (UNASUR) concluded in Peru today without the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven assisting presidents.
Efe has repeatedly attempted to access the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of the Unasur, but sources of the Foreign Ministry and the Presidency initially pointed out that they were going to deliver it after the closure, but later stated that it will be published at some point on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When they were consulted by the text, they pointed out that the content had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information from the Summit was restricted at all times.
During the day only the soundless video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room with the message "private session, audio restricted".
The little information circulated among reporters was delivered by the press spokespersons of some of the Unasur governments attending the appointment, although not the Peruvian.
The only document released during the day was the list of attending presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media asking for more data.
The Peruvian Presidency subsequently sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it is about Humala's statement, not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South America-Arab Summit (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, neither was the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced.
On the official website of ASPA it can be corroborated that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international appointments, the Peruvian authorities endeavored to ensure that there were safe broadcasting systems for all journalists, but limited the obtaining of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment by the Court of The Hague that addresses a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and of Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (CIJ), which begins on Monday in The Hague to hear the allegations of both sides, in the trial Lima filed against Santiago.
“We will comply with and execute the judgment that defines the differences we are bringing to this international court today,” Humala said, along with his Chilean pair.
“Chile has been, is and will remain a country that respects international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international courts,” Piñera said.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogotá Pact for which it had agreed to submit to the rulings of that international court, following a decision on maritime borders with Nicaragua that it considered seriously erroneous.
The summit was held with the inassistence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 following the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the appointment.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit, shortly after noon in Lima.
The president read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and the action lines for 31 projects between South American countries for a total of $17 billion in investments were set.
