With a Europe in crisis, “economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a triumphant matrix but must serve to broaden our productive matrix and glimpse a better future for our peoples,” Humala added.
“We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of South America’s spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a read message.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the transverse axes of their territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although it gave no further details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for his reintegration into the Union of South American Nations,” from which he is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region of prosperity and peace, and good neighbourly relations, was another of the issues underlined by the summit.
In this regard, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before starting his participation in the regional meeting he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan pair, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to deal in a respectful way with the maritime dispute following a ICJ ruling, questioned by Bogotá.
